A/B Test Sample Size Calculation

June 22, 2021 in A/B Testing
note-1
When designing an A/B test, it is imperative that we calculate the sample size. With the help of online calculators or softwares, we can easily calculate the sample size by filling in the significance level α, power (1-β), baseline value, minimum detectable effect or margin of error. This becomes handy as we don’t need to manually calculate the sample size ourselves. However, it might help to understand what the assumptions are, so that we can trust the outcome of the online calculators. This post is an effort in trying to show the math behind the sample size calculators. This post will derive a variation of mathematical equations used for calculating the sample size needed to compare two binomial proportions using a two-sided test with a significance level α and power 1-β.
Here are some reasons why we should be careful when calculating sample size for an A/B test.
  • •Many sample size formulae, with different underlying assumptions, may lead to an inaccurate outcome.
  • •The choice of the formula can impact importantly on the required sample size, particularly when for large detectable effects.
  • •There is variation in the sample size formulae and default settings implemented in statistical softwares or online calculators.
  • •Calculation of sample size using the default setting across statistical packages can result in important differences in sample size (some apply and some don't).
